  "runtimeMin": 72,
  "format": "A movie swap: Sean watches Amanda's pick, The English Patient, for the first time; Amanda revisits Sean's, Fargo. Both won big at the 1997 Oscars.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The English Patient",
      "note": "Amanda's pick — Sean's first watch",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The English Patient",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "Anthony Minghella's Best Picture winner, adapted from Michael Ondaatje's Booker Prize novel. A memory movie built around a burned Hungarian count (Ralph Fiennes) and the nurse (Juliette Binoche, Best Supporting Actress) caring for him. Shot by John Seale, produced by Saul Zaentz, edited by Walter Murch. Won nine Oscars; Sean grants the craft awards but questions its place in the canon, and both note the Miramax/Weinstein shadow over it."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Fargo",
      "note": "Sean's pick — Amanda's rewatch",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Fargo",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "The Coen brothers' sixth film and their mainstream breakout: a fake-true-crime kidnapping that spirals into a wood chipper. William H. Macy as the desperate car salesman, Steve Buscemi and Peter Stormare as the hitmen, Frances McDormand's Best Actress win as pregnant chief Marge (on screen barely 45 minutes). Roger Deakins shoots the snow; Amanda relitigates the Mike Yanagita scene and whether the Coens hold their characters in contempt."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Did the Oscars get it right?",
      "note": "the 1996 field and the swap verdict",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Jerry Maguire",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "Sean's curveball for the year's real best picture: the most 1996 movie he's ever seen, and one nobody at The Ringer under 30 has watched."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
